@summary Training delivery, measurable indicators, and sector-level positioning should not run as parallel workstreams; the design needs to join them up so each line of evidence makes the others more useful.

! conclusion: Training without indicators cannot show what changed. Indicators without sector positioning do not reach the bodies that could act on them. Sector positioning without a live training offer is positioning without product. The three lines only pay fully when they are joined up.

  + context: The current paper's background section identifies these three lines of evidence separately, then concludes that their parallel treatment is one of the main current failure modes.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: parallel evidence lines ↔ operationally joined evidence lines.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: joining the lines up requires more coordination and more role clarity than running each stream on its own.

  + THEN:
    Design the exchanges so training generates indicators-relevant evidence, indicators feed sector translation, and sector signals feed the next training and evaluation wave.

  + BECAUSE:
    Training without indicators cannot show what changed, indicators without sector positioning do not reach the bodies that could act on them, and sector positioning without a live training offer is positioning without product; the three lines only pay fully when they are joined up.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Wire training so it generates indicators-relevant evidence.
    - Route indicators into sector translation so they reach the bodies that can act.
    - Feed sector signals back into the next training and evaluation wave.
    - Add the coordination and role clarity the joined-up design requires.

